Q1. read.csv (base R) vs read_csv (tidyverse) vs fread (data.table)

There are quite a few utilities in R for reading plain text data files. Let us test the speed of reading a moderate sized compressed csv file, admissions.csv.gz, by three programs: read.csv in base R, read_csv in tidyverse, and fread in the popular data.table package.

Which function is fastest? Is there difference in the (default) parsed data types? (Hint: R function system.time measures run times.)

admissions <- "/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz"
#Base R
system.time(read.csv(admissions))
##    user  system elapsed 
##  41.860   0.274  42.148
#Tidyverse
system.time(read.csv(admissions))
##    user  system elapsed 
##  36.645   0.010  36.665
#fread
system.time(fread(admissions))
##    user  system elapsed 
##   1.298   0.101   0.820

The base R use 40.8 seconds, tidyverse use 35.1 seconds, and fread use 1.3 seconds. Fread is the fastest. I think the reason is that these commands work differently and fread tries to first read rows into memory as character and then tries to convert them into integer and factor as data types.

For later questions, we stick to the tidyverse.

  ggplot(patients_tble) +

  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
genderageplot

From this graph, I can tell that ICU has a high average age and the peak is around 67 years old. The chance of getting into ICU between 20 to 40 is low and are about the same. After 40 years old, it becomes more and more easier to get into ICU when the age increases.

genderageplot <-
  ggplot(patients_tble) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = anchor_age, y = gender)) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Gender",
       title = "ICU Admission Gender and Age Box Plot") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
genderageplot

From this graph, I can tell that female has a higher mean age of getting into ICU than male, and male gets into ICU earlier than female in their life on average. This is probably a side proof that female has a higher average lifetime than man do because if you get into ICU later, it means that you are healthier.)

  1. We are interested in the lab measurements of creatinine (50912), potassium (50971), sodium (50983), chloride (50902), bicarbonate (50882), hematocrit (51221), white blood cell count (51301), glucose (50931), magnesium (50960), and calcium (50893). Retrieve a subset of labevents.csv.gz only containing these items for the patients in icustays_tble as a tibble labevents_tble.

    Hint: labevents.csv.gz is a data file too big to be read in by the read_csv function in its default setting. Utilize the col_select and lazy options in the read_csv function to reduce the memory burden.

labevents_tble <- 
  read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/hosp/labevents_filtered_itemid.csv.gz",
           show_col_types = FALSE, col_select = c("subject_id", "itemid"), lazy = TRUE) %>%
  filter(itemid == "50912" | itemid == "50971" | itemid == "50983" | itemid == "50902" 
         | itemid == "50882" | itemid == "51221" | itemid == "51301" 
         | itemid == "50931" | itemid == "50960" | itemid == "50893") %>%
  semi_join(icustays_tble, by = "subject_id")
  1. Further restrict labevents_tble to the first lab measurement during the ICU stay.
labevents_tble <- distinct(labevents_tble, subject_id, .keep_all = TRUE)

We are interested in the vitals for ICU patients: heart rate (220045), mean non-invasive blood pressure (220181), systolic non-invasive blood pressure (220179), body temperature in Fahrenheit (223761), and respiratory rate (220210). Retrieve a subset of chartevents.csv.gz only containing these items for the patients in icustays_tble as a tibble chartevents_tble.
chartevents_tble <- 
  read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/icu/chartevents_filtered_itemid.csv.gz",
           show_col_types = FALSE, col_select = c("subject_id", "itemid"), lazy = TRUE) %>%
  semi_join(icustays_tble, by = "subject_id") %>%
  filter(itemid == "220045" | itemid == "220181" | itemid == "220179" 
         | itemid == "223761" | itemid == "220210") %>%
  rename(veid = itemid)
  1. Further restrict chartevents_tble to the first vital measurement during the ICU stay.
chartevents_tble <- distinct(chartevents_tble, subject_id, .keep_all = TRUE)
  1. Summarize these vital measurements by appropriate numerics and graphics. heart rate (220045), mean non-invasive blood pressure (220181), systolic non-invasive blood pressure (220179), body temperature in Fahrenheit (223761), and respiratory rate (220210).
ggplot(chartevents_tble, aes(x = factor(veid))) +
  geom_bar(fill = "lightblue", colour = "black") +
    labs(x = "Vital Measurements", ylab = "Count", 
       title = "The Count of The First Vital Measurement Done to a Patient in ICU") +
  geom_text(aes(label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = -0.2, color = "black") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("220045" = "heart rate",
                              "220181" = "mean non-invasive blood pressure",
                              "220179" = "systolic non-invasive blood pressure",
                              "223761" = "body temperature in Fahrenheit",
                              "220210" = "respiratory rate")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, vjust = 1)) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(..count../sum(..count..))),
              stat = 'count', vjust = 1.3)

Q7. Putting things together

Let us create a tibble mimic_icu_cohort for all ICU stays, where rows are

  • first ICU stay of each unique adult (age at admission > 18)

and columns contain at least following variables

  • all variables in icustays.csv.gz
  • all variables in admission.csv.gz
  • all variables in patients.csv.gz
  • first lab measurements during ICU stay
  • first vital measurements during ICU stay
  • an indicator variable thirty_day_mort whether the patient died within 30 days of hospital admission (30 day mortality)
mimic_icu_cohort <-
  inner_join(icustays_tble, admissions_tble, by = "subject_id") %>%
  inner_join(patients_tble, by = "subject_id") %>%
  inner_join(labevents_tble, by = "subject_id") %>%
  inner_join(chartevents_tble, by = "subject_id")
mimic_icu_cohort <-
  add_column(mimic_icu_cohort, thirty_day_mort = if_else(
    difftime(mimic_icu_cohort$deathtime, mimic_icu_cohort$admittime, unit = "day") <= 30,
    "Died within 30 Days of hospital admission", "Not Died in 30 Days of hospital admission", "Not Died in 30 Days of hospital admission"))
